    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-08T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-08T09:00:00-05:00" n="539"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d539">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">511.4R1/12: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-08T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 8, 1931—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 8—2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>118. Legation’s despatch No. 2094, June 19, 1931.<note n="26" xml:id="d539fn26"
                        >Not printed.</note> Ekstrand<note n="27" xml:id="d539fn27">Eric Einar
                        Ekstrand, chairman of the Inquiry Commission in 1930 and director of the
                        Opium Traffic and Social Questions sections of the League of Nations
                        Secretariat.</note> has just called to explain how anxiously he and the
                    others interested in this conference are hoping for a favorable response from
                    the United States.</p>
                <p>Delevingne,<note n="28" xml:id="d539fn28">Sir Malcolm Delevingne, Permanent
                        Deputy-Under-Secretary of State in the British Home Department.</note> Van
                        Wettum,<note n="29" xml:id="d539fn29">W. G. van Wettum, Adviser to the
                        Netherlands Government for International Opium Affairs.</note> Kusama,<note
                        n="30" xml:id="d539fn30">Of the Japanese Foreign Office.</note> Marshall
                    from India<note n="31" xml:id="d539fn31">J. B. Marshall, Excise Commissioner of
                        Burma.</note> and probably Bourgois<note n="32" xml:id="d539fn32">G.
                        Bourgois, French Consul at Bangkok.</note> will attend.</p>
                <p>The conference begins on November 9th and its anticipated duration is 3 weeks. As
                    very little time remains before those participating must start their voyage
                    Ekstrand begs to learn the decision of our Government at the earliest convenient
                    date.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
